

Problem statement: 
Most biological processes require many genes working in tandem in pathways. Gene data is listed by gene, rs variant, and protein, not at the system level. It makes sense that a pathway that contains multiple subclinical (but known adversive) rs variants in different genes might not function at the same rate or capacity vs a pathway that has a light adverse rs variant load. 


Solution: A product that uncovers genetic medical phenotypes at the pathway level and reports back to a user in laymans terms.

Parts: 
User Interface with LLM to translate user requests into queries
  Example: "My doctor prescribed this new medication called asprin. Will this work for me?"
  Example2: "My grandmother went blind at 75. What are my chances of the same?"
  Example3: "I am exhaused all the time. Why?"
Input - compressed vcf file
Referenced Data
  dbSNP
  KEGG Pathway
Output - reports or chat

Functions: 
File parsing
Joins
variant normalization
Personalized Pathway Build

Additional requirements: 
I want this to be secure (no leaks of personal genomic data)
I want this to be efficient (no need to store data if we can access it easily and inexpensively) (no need to process the same data over and over if we can store it inexpensively)
I want this to be cheap (no expensive accounts for AI or databases or hosting) We need to understand the data that exists, including the shape of it and how we access it. 
I also want to vet each decision that we make so that we don't just go with the first solution to a problem.


